\centering
\includegraphics[width=10cm]{3.eps}
\caption{The geographical correlation $GC(n)$ on the geographical parameter $n$ is displayed for the SH and SZ. The stars, circles and triangles are for the year 2005-2006, 2007-2008 and 2009-2010, respectively. \label{f2}}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=10cm]{4.eps}
\caption{The geographical correlation $GC(n)$ of the shuffled data on the geographical parameter $n$ is displayed, with the results being the average over 100 runs. The panels (a), (c), (e) are for the year 2005-2006, 2007-2008, 2009-2010 of the SH, and (b), (d), (f) are for the year 2005-2006, 2007-2008, 2009-2010 of the SZ, respectively. The stems suggest the error bar. \label{f3}}
\end{figure}

The results are confirmed by calculating the geographical correlation of the shuffled data, which are generated by taking an average over a 100-run of shuffling procedure for the location of stocks. The geographical correlation $GC(n)$ on $n$ is shown in Fig. 4 for the shuffled data. Different from the original data, the $GC(n)$ is found to be stable for different geographical parameter $n$. It suggests that the stock location indeed has an impact on the market correlation. And the stock correlation in the financial crisis time is always higher than that before and after the financial crisis, which is also consistent with that observed in the real market data.

