\section*{Distance effect on stock correlation}

Internet shortens the distance of the world, and it becomes quite easy to access information. Then, should it change the geographical distance role in the stock markets, and should the long distance weaken the stock connections? To answer this question, we firstly investigate the stock distance distribution. The stock distance for the stock pairs inside each province is calculated. As shown in Fig. 5, a two-stage exponential decay of the distance distribution is observed for both the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock markets, with a crossover at about 87 kilometer for the SH and 102 kilometer for the SZ. For the distance less than the crossover point, the decay of the distribution is much faster than that of the distance greater than the crossover point. That is, the probability of the short distance is much greater than that of the long distance. The crossover phenomenon of the stock distance distribution indicates that the companies are prone to set their headquarters close to each other. The possible explanation could be that it is more convenient for companies to communicate for the short distance, while the long distance may hinder the communications.


